            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Now let’s talk about general geometric sequences and series.
A geometric sequence is defined by an <em>initial term</em> <m>a</m> and <em>constant ratio</em> <m>r</m>, and looks like this:
<me>
    a,\,ar,\,ar^{2},\,ar^{3},\,\ldots.
</me>
Partial geometric sums are just the partial sums of geometric sequences. That is, sums of the form
<me>
    S_{n} = a + ar + \cdots + ar^{n-1}= \sum_{i=1}^{n}ar^{i-1}.
</me>
Infinite geometric sums, on the other hand, are the limits of the partial sums (whenever these limits exist), and look like this:
<me>
    \lim_{n\to\infty}S_{n} = \lim_{n\to\infty}\big(a+ar+\cdots+ar^{n-1}\big) = \sum_{i=1}^{\infty} ar^{i-1}.
</me>

                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                In a previous problem, the areas that you calculated were geometric sums with a specific initial term and constant ratio.  What was the initial term <m>a</m> in these sums?  The constant ratio <m>r</m>?
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                In a previous problem, we came up with a simplified expression for the area of the shaded region after <m>n</m> steps.
We will generalize this expression.
Let <m>a</m> and <m>r</m> be arbitrary numbers with <m>r\neq 1</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Using the original definition of <m>S_{n}</m>, expand and then simplify <m>S_{n}-rS_{n}</m>. (Hint: Group like terms.
Most of them should cancel.)
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                If you did the above calculation carefully, you should get an answer similar to <m>S_{n}-rS_{n}=a-ar^{n}</m>.  Solve this equation to come up with a simple formula for <m>S_{n}</m>.  Check that this formula agrees with your formula from the first problem.

                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Recall that the value of a series is defined to be the limit of its partial sums, so that
<me>
    \lim_{n\to\infty}\big(a+ar+\cdots +ar^{n-1}\big) = \sum_{i=1}^{\infty} ar^{i-1}= \lim_{n\to\infty}S_{n} = \lim_{n\to\infty}\underline{\hspace{5cm}}.
</me>

                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               Based on your formula for <m>S_{n}</m>, what can you say about the convergence or divergence of <m>S_{n}</m>?
                               Does it depend on <m>a</m>? Does it depend on <m>r</m>? For what values of <m>r</m> does the series converge? For what values does it diverge?

                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                Using your formula for <m>S_{n}</m>, take limits to come up with a formula for the value of the sum of a general infinite geometric series.  Check that this formula agrees with the area of the square in the very first problem.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>
                </exercise>
